\i0  such those in as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/65/rr/rr6501e1er.htm"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf4 CDC Guideline for Prescribing Opioids for Chronic Pain}} are used to make rules and regulations about medications that leave little or no room for physicians\'92 discretion and individual patient needs. How does this impact people who depend on these medications to avoid suffering and have a decent quality of life?\
In a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOFDotetvCQ"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 medical presentation}}, addiction expert, primary care physician, and researcher, Stefan Kertesz, M.D. from the University of Alabama, Birmingham, said he believes that the 2016 \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdc.gov/drugoverdose/prescribing/guideline.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 CDC Guideline for Prescribing Opioids for Chronic Pain}}\'94 \'96 \'93the manifest\'94 now guiding medical use of opioid medications for chronic pain \'96 is \'93mostly sound\'94 and \'93a relatively high quality product.\'94 However, he expressed great concern about \'93emerging practices that defy the CDC Guideline, misconstrue epidemiology, misunderstand the complexity of what causes addiction, and suspend our customary rules of medical decision-making.\'94 He added, \'93Ethical expectations that are core to being a health provider are being violated in the care of pain patients.\'94\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Are Universal Opioid Prescription Cut-Offs Stipulated?\cf3 \
Dr. Kertesz is talking about\
such practices as establishing \'93cut-offs\'94 or strict upper limits when prescribing opioids. Even though the CDC Guideline makes no such stipulations and has no authority to restrict prescribing, it appears that a growing number of medical facilities and physicians have interpreted its recommendation concerning dosages that way. (To be able to compare dosages of different opioids in like units, all opioids can be converted to an equivalent of one medication, morphine, using a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/providers/health-topics/mme-calculator.page"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 morphine equivalent dose calculator}} to calculate \'93morphine milligram equivalents\'94 or MME/day.)\
\
To illustrate his concerns, Kertesz showed a photo of an actual flyer from a doctor\'92s office that reads (literally), \'93Beginning February 2017 Morphine Equivalency Dosing WILL decrease until CDC guidelines are met by June 2017. Target is 90 mg of Morphine equivalency per day, or less. All medication adjustments will be based on this new clinic policy.\'94\
\
What does the CDC Guideline, in fact, say? Pointing out that the higher the dosage, the higher the risk of overdose death from opioids, its recommendation does recommend special caution at total daily dose thresholds of 50 to 90 MME. As an upper limit it specifies that clinicians should avoid increasing opioid daily dosages to no more than the equivalent of 90 MME. Yet it adds, 
\i \'93or carefully justify a decision to titrate dosage to more than that.\'94
\i0  Note the the 
\i leeway
\i0  for physicians to use their judgment about higher dosages in consideration of 
\i individual
\i0  patients\'92 needs. There\'92s also advice to consider consultation with pain specialists. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2017/08/23/543955887/intent-on-reversing-its-opioid-epidemic-a-state-limits-prescriptions"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Some states}} have their own rules concerning thresholds for opioid prescribing.)
